This project focuses on converting RGB images into 4-level grayscale images using Floyd–Steinberg error diffusion dithering
to preserve image details. After quantization, the images are compressed using Run-Length Encoding (RLE), 
which reduces the storage size while retaining the essential visual information.

On the decoding side, the RLE data is processed to reconstruct the grayscale images, and each pixel is
mapped to an ASCII character using the same pattern as in the encoding process. The project automates the
entire workflow, allowing multiple images to be encoded and decoded seamlessly, producing both
compressed text files and human-readable ASCII representations.
